Leading Edge Scaffolding. Rather proud of this one. The mark (a monogram of sorts) was constructed to portray the ‘leading edge’; the unprotected side and edge of a floor, roof, or formwork for a floor or other walking/working surface which changes location as additional floor, roof, decking or formwork sections are placed, formed or constructed. Also the companies namesake. Can you see the L + E?

Another 2.5 method. More often than not the grid and other elements created will revolve around the initial shape; In this case an ellipse. After the initial group had been created I was mainly concerned with the height of newly created groups and maintaining proportions. Understanding the relationship between these groups helps you to understand the design as a whole, which in my opinion, is the main point of a grid. Do it often enough and most of the time the grid will exist only in your mind.
